How Python achieves OOP concepts
1Ô∏è‚É£ Class & Object (base of OOP)

Real life:
Class = Blueprint
Object = Real thing made from it

class Car:
    def start(self):
        print("Car started")

my_car = Car()   # object
my_car.start()
Python uses the class keyword to create classes
üëâ Objects are created by calling the class

2Ô∏è‚É£ Encapsulation (data protection)
Real life:
ATM machine ‚Üí you can withdraw money, but you can‚Äôt touch cash inside

In Python:
Real life:
ATM machine ‚Üí you can withdraw money, but you can‚Äôt touch cash inside
class Account:
    def __init__(self, balance):
        self.__balance = balance   # private variable

    def get_balance(self):
        return self.__balance
__balance is private

Access only through methods

üëâ Python achieves encapsulation using:

Access modifiers (_, __)

Getter & setter methods

3Ô∏è‚É£ Inheritance (reusability)

Real life:
Child inherits features from parents

class Vehicle:
    def start(self):
        print("Vehicle started")

class Car(Vehicle):
    pass

c = Car()
c.start()
Car automatically gets start() from Vehicle
4Ô∏è‚É£ Polymorphism (many forms)

Real life:
Same word ‚Äúrun‚Äù:

run a program

run a race

In Python:
class Dog:
    def sound(self):
        print("Bark")

class Cat:
    def sound(self):
        print("Meow")

animals = [Dog(), Cat()]

for a in animals:
    a.sound()
5Ô∏è‚É£ Abstraction (hide complexity)

Real life:
Car pedals ‚Üí you drive, you don‚Äôt know engine logic
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod

class Shape(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def area(self):
        pass


